SIMPLE: prescription
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prescription
<hw>Pre*scrip"tion</hw> <pr>(pr⟦esl⟧*skr⟦icr⟧p"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>prescription</ets>, L.
<ets>praescriptio</ets>, an inscription, preface, precept, demurrer,
prescription (in sense 3), fr. <ets>praescribere</ets>. See
<er>Prescribe</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of prescribing, directing, or dictating;
direction; precept; also, that which is prescribed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A direction of a remedy or of
remedies for a disease, and the manner of using them; a medical recipe;
also, a prescribed remedy.</def> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>a written
order from a physician for a medication, which allows a patient to
legally obtain medication which is required by law to be dispensed only
on authorization from a physician or other qualified medical
practitioner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A prescribing for title; the claim
of title to a thing by virtue of immemorial use and enjoyment; the right
or title acquired by possession had during the time and in the manner
fixed by law.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That profound reverence for law and <qex>prescription</qex> which
has long been characteristic of Englishmen.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Prescription</xex> differs from <xex>custom</xex>,
which is a local usage, while <xex>prescription</xex> is personal,
annexed to the person only. <xex>Prescription</xex> only extends to
incorporeal rights, such as a right of way, or of common. What the law
gives of <xex>common rights</xex> is not the subject of
<xex>prescription</xex>. <au>Blackstone</au>. <au>Cruise</au>.
<au>Kent</au>. In Scotch law, <xex>prescription</xex> is employed in the
sense in which <xex>limitation</xex> is used in England and America,
namely, to express that operation of the lapse of time by which
obligations are extinguished or title protected. <au>Sir T. Craig.</au>
<au>Erskine</au>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prescriptive</ent>⟦br⟧
